<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910515-0131</DOCNO><DOCID>910515-0131.</DOCID><HL>   Allied-Signal to Settle Suit</HL><DATE>05/15/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ALD</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>CANADA (CN)NEW JERSEY (NJ)</RE><LP>   MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. -- Allied-Signal Corp. said itagreed to pay $25,000 to the U.S. government to settle acivil suit brought against the company for failing to complywith regulations regarding the export of certain chemicals.   In the suit, the government claimed that Allied-Signalfailed to comply with record-keeping requirements regardingshipment of acetone to Canada. Under U.S. governmentstatutes, all export shipments of chemicals that can bediverted for use in manufacturing illicit drugs require 15days' advance notice.</LP><TEXT>   While the settlement is not an official admission ofwrongdoing, an Allied-Signal spokesman called the violation atechnical error that stemmed from an oversight in theshipping department.</TEXT></DOC>